DURBAN - Repairs have been completed on the main pipe feeding the Woodlands reservoir after it burst on Sunday. The eThekwini Municipality said in a statement on its Facebook page this afternoon that, capacity was building at the Woodlands 3 & 4 and downstream reservoirs and residents would start receiving water tomorrow.On Monday, Ward 64 councillor Gavin Hegter confirmed that a 1.2m main pipe feeding the Woodlands reservoir burst.This reservoir supplies water to areas in the south of Durban.The city said the following areas will experience water shortages and some are already affected:MORE ON THISTap water is not contaminated and safe to drink, says eThekwini Municipality•   Isipingo,•   Isipingo Hills,•   Malabar Hills,•   Lotus Park,°   Ezimbokodweni°   Athlone Park,°   Amanzimtoti,°   Old Durban Airport,°   Lower Illovo,°   Doonside,°   Lewis Dr,°   Garden Lots,°   Southgate,°    Smithfield,°    Karidene Beach,°    Lovu Beach,°    Panorama Park,°    Midnight Cafe,°    Crowder,°    Clanstal,°    Craigieburn,°    Umkhomazi,°    Singhs,°    Naidooville,°    Magabheni,°    KwaMakhutha,°    Adams Mission,°    Umbumbulu,°    Mgodi,°    Imfume,°    Ehlanzeni,°    Mnini,°    Mashiwane,°    Amahlongwa,The city said water tankers are on standby to respond to affected areas.“The municipality apologises for the inconvenience caused and thanked residents for their patience.”THE MERCURY